1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Ba3 {
This is the first of a group of three systems (also including 7.Qa4+ and 7.
Bb5+) aiming at crossing Black's most natural queenside plan, ...c7-c5
followed by ...Nc6. But all these lines imply early white commitments in a
moment when Black is very flexible still, so they do not pose objective
problems. At the same time, one has to know what he is doing as the character
of play deviates from the usual course. The move examined in this line
prevents ...c7-c5 physically, but this will not last. Besides, the bishop is
far from the optimal square on e3, leaving the d4-pawn somewhat vulnerable.} Nd7
{It is best to speed up the queenside counterattack, to create the
potential threat ...cxd4 and ...Qa5+ before White gets castled. True, the
knight will not go to c6 anymore, but the a3 bishop will also be anything but
a well-placed piece.} 8. Nf3 {The most natural developing move. Others could
transpose, but White gets only coordinating problems if trying developing the
knight on e2 or inserting a rook move on the way.} (8. Qb3 c5 9. Rd1 O-O 10.
Be2 (10. Nf3 Qa5 11. Be2 {is a more obvious move order, but it just
transposes.}) 10... Qa5 11. Nf3 cxd4 12. Bb4 {The only way of maintaining the
central integrity.} Qb6 ({The passing of time does not necessarily imply
progress. The last move was played almost a century ago while the weaker} 12...
Qc7 {occured in a modern game:} 13. cxd4 Nf6 14. Qe3 $14 {With space advantage
to White Milov-Mikhalevski, Biel 2002.}) 13. cxd4 {Michell-Torre Repetto,
Marienbad 1925} a5 $1 14. Ba3 (14. Bxe7 Qxb3 15. axb3 Re8 16. Bg5 Rxe4 $15)
14... Qxb3 15. axb3 a4 $132) (8. Bc4 c5 9. Qb3 O-O 10. Ne2 {deviating from the
main line places the knight on a slightly unfavourable square.} cxd4 11. cxd4
Nb6 12. Rd1 (12. Bd3 Be6 13. Qb4 f5 $132 {With the knight on f3 this would run
into problems after Ng5.}) {In Denisov-Tarasov, Izhevsk 2013 Black had no
reasons to refrain from} 12... Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Qa5+ {for instance} 14. Qc3 Qa4
15. Qb3 Qxb3 16. axb3 Re8 17. h4 Bd7 $132) 8... c5 9. Qb3 {Since he will not
be in time getting castled before things get tense on the queenside, White
prepares meeting ...Qa5 followed by ...cxd4 with Bb4.} (9. Bc4 {should lead to
a transposition:} cxd4 10. Qb3 (10. Bxf7+ $2 {is a unsound sacrifice.} Kxf7 11.
Ng5+ Ke8 12. Ne6 Qb6 13. Nxg7+ Kf7 $19 {Jimenez Ruano-Garcia Marin, Barbera
del Valles 2014.}) 10... O-O 11. cxd4 {reaching a later subline.}) ({The
queen's development typical for the Be3 lines examined in the previous article
is not sound here as the bishop is exposed on a3.} 9. Qd2 Qa5 10. Bb2 Nb6 11.
Rd1 Bg4 $15 {Belakovskaia-Ruchieva, Simferopol 1992.}) 9... O-O 10. Be2 {
The most solid bishop's development, but not one suiting the seemingly
aggressive queenside setup. True, all the alternatives have drawbacks.} (10.
Rd1 {sets a small trap:} Qc7 $1 ({The hurried} 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf6 12. Bd3
{offers White an extra tempo on a subline below. Concretely, after
} Bg4 {he has} 13. Bb1 {as the d4-pawn is defended and if} Qa5+ 14. Bb4 $14)
11. Be2 (11. Bd3 {exposes the bishop to} b5 12. Bb1 {For the pawn grabbing
refer to the lines below.} a5 13. O-O Ba6 $17 {Flohr-Tolush, Tallinn 1945.})
11... b5 $1 12. O-O (12. Qxb5 cxd4 13. O-O dxc3 14. Bxe7 c2 15. Rc1 Re8 16. Bh4
Bb7 $11) (12. Bxb5 Rb8 13. Qc4 Qa5 14. Bxd7 Qxa3 15. Bxc8 Rfxc8 $36) 12... a6
13. e5 Bb7 14. h4 e6 15. h5 Rfc8 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. Ng5 $11 {½-½
Gurevich-Atakisi, Istanbul 2006.}) (10. Bd3 {exposes the bishop in a familiar
way:} Rb8 11. O-O b5 $132) (10. Bc4 {runs into} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb6 $1 12. Be2 (
12. O-O Nxc4 13. Qxc4 Bg4 14. Ne5 Be6 15. Qb4 Re8 16. Rfd1 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qc7
18. f4 a5 {Due to the weakness on e4, it turns out that Black's king is
actually safer than his colleague in this interesting middlegame with opposite
colored bishops.} 19. Qb5 Qc2 20. Qxb7 Rab8 21. Qa7 Qxe4 {Only Black can be
slightly better, Stopa-Kazakov, Wroclaw 2004.}) 12... Be6 13. Qb4 {White is
forced keeping moving with already developed pieces, giving Black the time to
carry out his plan.} Rc8 {Preparing the invasion of the c4-square.} 14. O-O (
14. Qxe7 Bc4 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. e5 f6 {with excellent compensation for the
pawn due to the perfect developing. If} 17. Be7 $2 Re8 18. exf6 Bxf6 $1 19.
Bxf6 Rxe2+ 20. Kd1 Rxf2 $19) 14... Bc4 15. Rfe1 Bxe2 16. Rxe2 Nc4 17. Rd1 (17.
Qxe7 Bxd4 $15) 17... Qd6 18. Qxd6 (18. e5 {as played in Le, Q-Svidler, Astana
2012 weakens the light squares. With the bishop on a3 White's attacking
chances based on the control over f6 are slim.} Qa6 $1 19. Bc1 e6 $15) 18...
exd6 19. Bc1 Rfe8 20. Bf4 b5 $15 {The relative weakness on d6 is less relevant
than the active queenside setup, as White's center is not too mobile,
Milov-Svidler, Moscow 2001.}) 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf6 {This simple way of
attacking e4 reveals the drawback of White's whole setup. He has invested too
much time in committal moves while his king still is in the center.} 12. e5 (
12. Bd3 Bg4 {leaves the center hanging.}) 12... Nd5 13. O-O b6 14. Ng5 h6 15.
Bf3 Bb7 16. Ne4 Qd7 17. Rab1 (17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Rad1 Rfd8 19. e6 fxe6 20. Bg4
Rc6 21. Bc1 Bc8 $11 {Atalik-Lin,W Beijing 1997.}) 17... Rab8 $5 {Defending
against Nc5.} 18. Nd6 $5 {In case of neutral play, Black's position is very
comfortable strategically so White tries changing the course of the game.} exd6
19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Rfd8 21. exd6 Bf8 22. Rfe1 Rbc8 23. Qf3 (23. g3 Bxd6 24.
Bxd6 Rc6 $15 (24... Qxd6 $4 25. Re8+ $1 $18)) 23... Bxd6 24. Bb2 Rc2 $1 ({
More active and ambitious than} 24... Qf5 25. Qxf5 gxf5 26. Rbc1 Bf8 {
Gagunashvili-Mchedlishvili Tbilisi 2015.}) 25. d5 {This is what Black might
have feared as his bishop is not on the long diagonal.} (25. Qd3 Qf5 $17 {
gains a whole tempo over the game.}) 25... Bc5 26. Rf1 (26. Re2 Rxe2 27. Qxe2
Qxd5 $17) (26. Qf6 $2 Bxf2+ 27. Kh1 Rxb2 28. Qxb2 Bxe1 29. Rxe1 Qxd5 $19) 26...
Qf5 $17 *

