1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+ {
Moving the queen so early is an even higher commitment than 7.Ba3, but White
relies on the fact that the queen's mobility will allow him retrieving the
harmony after achieving the initial aim of taking Black away from the usual
paths.} Nd7 {A flexible developing move. Black plans simply ...c7-c5 followed
by ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 with active queenside play.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 {
Once again this is the most solid answer.} (9. Bg5 c5 10. Rc1 a6 11. Qa3 (11.
Be2 b5 $1 12. Bxb5 $2 Nb6 $1) 11... Qc7 12. Bd3 b5 $5 $146 13. Bxb5 (13. O-O
Bb7 $11) 13... axb5 14. Qxa8 Bb7 15. Qa3 Bxe4 {Pawns are equal but White's
coordination is very poor, and his pawns are weak. These offer Black ample
compensation.} 16. O-O Qb7 17. Ne1 {Otherwise a double capture on f3 would
most likely lead to a draw by perpetual.} Ra8 18. Qb2 e6 {White will soon have
problems defending a2.} 19. Be3 cxd4 20. Bxd4 e5 21. Be3 Bf8 {Followed by ...
Bd5 soon. White is way too passive to claim an advantage.}) 9... c5 10. O-O {
If White delays castling, Black could switch to the familiar plan based on ...
Nf6.} (10. Be3 Nf6 ({The main line maneuver} 10... Nb6 {is also good, of
course, but it has occurred only in a game between low rated players:} 11. Qb3
cxd4 12. cxd4 Be6 13. Qb4 Rc8 14. O-O Bc4 $11 {Milovanova-Kvachko, St
Petersburg 2015.}) 11. Bd3 {A more or less forced waste of time.} (11. Nd2 Ng4
12. Bxg4 Bxg4 13. f3 Bd7 14. Qb3 cxd4 15. cxd4 {Korobov-Obodchuk, Moscow 2002}
Be6 {Attacking the pinned d4-pawn.} 16. Qb2 Qb6 17. Nb3 Rfd8 18. Rd1 a5 {
with an initiative for Black.}) (11. e5 Nd5) {In Danner-Birnboim, Lugano 1989
Black could have used his slight lead in development for harmonious regrouping:
} 11... b6 12. O-O (12. d5 e6 $15) (12. Ne5 Bb7 13. f3 Nh5 14. Be2 Bxe5 15.
dxe5 Qc7 16. f4 Rad8 {We have seen this picture before. White's kingside pawns
are not that threatening as the e4-square is weak, the same as the whole
queenside structure. At the same time, Black's queenside pawns restrict the
potentially dangerous dark-squared bishop.} 17. O-O Qc6 18. Qxc6 Bxc6 19. f5
Bxe4 20. Bh6 Rfe8 21. fxg6 hxg6 22. Bb5 Bd3 23. Bxe8 Bxf1 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 25.
Rxf1+ Kg8 26. g4 Ng7 $11) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bb7 $11 14. d5 $6 e6 $15) (10.
Bg5 {leaves the d4-pawn vulnerable:} Nf6 11. Qc2 (11. Bd3 Bd7 12. Qa3 cxd4 13.
cxd4 Bg4 $11) {Sanikidze-Popov, Denizli 2013} 11... Qc7 12. Bd3 (12. d5 $2 Nxe4
$1 $19) 12... Nh5 {Threatening ...Nf4.} 13. Qd2 Bg4 {with initiative.}) 10...
Nb6 {The safest plan.} ({Black's position may be objectively all right after} 
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc5 12. dxc5 Bxa1 13. e5 {but with the bishop's retreat
cut off I would fear White's attack.}) ({In the absence of White's bishop's
commitment,} 10... Nf6 {is less effective:} 11. Bd3 b6 12. Re1 Bb7 13. Bf4 {
keeping the integrity of the center.}) 11. Qa3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 {Now that
White has committed Be3 this is effective.} 13. Bg5 (13. Rd1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 ({
Keeping the control over c4 for if} 14. Bxf3 Bxd4 15. Bg5 Nc4 16. Qb4 b5 {
The pawn is taboo due to ...Nd6 winning an exchange.} 17. Bxe7 Qb6 18. Bxf8 a5
19. Qe7 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 Rxf8 $11) 14... e6 (14... Bxd4 15. Bg5 Bxa1 16. Rxd8
Rfxd8 17. Qxe7 Rd7 18. Qa3 Bd4 $6 19. Bb5 Rc7 20. Qd6 $16 {Riazantsev-Navara,
Montpellier 2015.}) 15. Be3 Qh4 16. Qb3 Bh6 17. a4 Rac8 18. a5 Nd7 19. Rac1 Nf6
20. Bxh6 Qxh6 21. Qe3 Qh4 22. f4 Nh5 23. Bxh5 Qxh5 $15 {
Moiseenko-Lorparizangeneh, Doha 2015.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qxd4 15. Rad1 Qe5 {
White will retrieve the pawn retaining the bishops pair, but Black's minor
pieces are very active. On of his main aim is installing the knight on c3.} 16.
Bxe7 (16. Qxe7 {helps Black in carrying out his main plan:} Qxe7 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 18.
Bg5 Na4 19. Be3 Re7 20. Bg5 Ree8 21. Be3 Re7 22. Bg5 Ree8 {½-½ Klein-Bok,
Haarlem 2013.}) 16... Rfe8 17. Bh4 (17. Bd6 Qb2 $11) 17... Qc3 18. Qxc3 Bxc3
19. Rd3 Rac8 20. e5 (20. Rc1 Na4 {followed by ...b7-b5.}) (20. Rb1 Na4 21. Rdd1
(21. Rd7 Nc5 22. Rdd1 Be5 $11) 21... b6 22. Rd7 a6 23. Ra7 Bd4 24. Rxa6 Nc3 25.
Re1 Ra8 26. Rxa8 Rxa8 $11) 20... Bxe5 21. Bxb7 Rc4 22. Bg5 Kg7 23. g3 Rb8 {
Black is very active, so White decided to provoke an exchange leading to an
obvious draw:} 24. Bd5 $11 {Thejkumar-Ghosh, Dubai 2016.} *

