1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bb5+ {
From the whole group of systems, this implies the smallest commitment as after
provoking the desired effect that Bishop can return quickly to a favorable
square. But the main drawback of the last move is speeding up Black's
queenside expansion, true, in a rather unusual way.} c6 8. Ba4 (8. Bc4 {
transposes} b5 (8... c5 {transposes to the main line with 7.Bc4, but
this does not suit our general repertoire since in that case, I have
recommended the plan based on ...Nc6.}) {White has nothing better than 9.Bb3
transposing to the main line since} 9. Be2 b4 {leaves the bishop passive on e2.
}) 8... b5 (8... O-O 9. Ne2 c5 {is entirely viable, as the bishop does not
stand better on a4 than on c4 as in the 7.Bc4 system. But given the move order
mentioned above, it does not make sense examining this for our repertoire.
Instead, I recommend one of Adorjan's specialties, yielding his numerous
successes in the '90s.}) 9. Bb3 b4 {An unusual but quite effective way of
undermining White's center, enabled by the loss of time caused by the bishop's
repeated moving around. After exchanging the c3-pawn, Black will usually play 
Ba6, either preventing White from castling if he plays Nf3 or putting the
d4-pawn under severe pressure after Ne2. In practice, White has tried out
many moves.} 10. Qf3 (10. Ne2 {places the knight under the bishop's pressure
after the expected ...Ba6.} bxc3 11. Be3 Ba6 12. Rc1 Nd7 13. e5 O-O ({This is
the simplest, but the following Adorjan game deserves mentioning:} 13... Qa5
14. Qc2 c5 15. Qe4 $2 {This loses too much time. 15.f4 is preferable.} O-O 16.
Bxf7+ Kh8 17. Nf4 Rxf7 18. Qxa8+ Rf8 19. Qd5 Qb5 20. Qb3 cxd4 21. Qxb5 Bxb5 22.
Ne6 dxe3 23. Nxf8 Nxe5 {0-1 Giorgadze-Adorjan, Debrecen 1992.}) 14. e6 $5 (14.
O-O c5 $15) (14. f4 Rc8 15. Rxc3 Nb6 16. Rc5 Nd5 17. Bd2 e6 18. O-O Re8 $15 {
followed by ...Bf8 and ...c6-c5.}) 14... fxe6 15. Bxe6+ (15. Nf4 Rxf4 $1 16.
Bxf4 Kh8 $5 17. Bxe6 Qa5 $1 18. Bxd7 Rd8 19. Qg4 e5 20. Bg5 Rf8 {with a
crushing attack despite the missing rook.}) 15... Kh8 {Both sides have
weaknesses, but White's structure is slightly more compact. However, the
control over d5 and the bishops' activity offer Black at least equal play.} 16.
O-O (16. Rxc3 Nf6 {Planning ...Qd6 possibly followed by ...Ng4. The c6-pawn is
taboo due to ...Bb7 since the g2-pawn is hanging.} 17. f3 {Cotrolling g4.} Nd5
18. Bxd5 Qxd5 {with excellent play.}) {Atalik-Rytshagov, Ikaria 1994} 16... Nf6
17. Rxc3 Qd6 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. Rxc4 Ng4 20. Ng3 Nxe3 21. fxe3 e5 {with some
light initiative.}) (10. Bb2 {this looks logical as it gains time for
developing but the bishop will be slightly hanging on c3.} bxc3 11. Bxc3 O-O
12. Qd2 ({The insertion of} 12. h4 h5 {does not change anything essentially.}
13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Nf3 Ba6 15. Rc1 {Dao,T -Fogarasi, Budapest 1995} Qb6 $11) 12...
Nd7 13. f4 (13. Rc1 Ba6 14. Ne2 e5 $11 {Dao,T-Boros, Hungary 1997}) 13... Ba6
14. Nf3 e6 (14... c5 {is also possible but the main line consolidates Black's
position allowing him preparing his counterplay at his leisure while the
white king is still struggling.}) 15. Rd1 Qb6 16. e5 c5 17. Kf2 Rac8 18. Qe3
Rfd8 19. Ng5 Bb7 20. Rhe1 h6 21. Ne4 Bf8 $15 {After Black's global regrouping
White's position starts hanging a bit, Sokolov-Stohl, Austria 1994.}) (10. Nf3
bxc3 11. O-O {is a harmonious way of getting castled, but the knight is exposed
to ...Bg4 and besides White still needs time for retrieving the pawn.} O-O 12.
Bg5 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 {Kruppa-Khachiyan, Cappelle-la-Grande 1999} Bxd4
$5 ({If Black intends avoiding complications, preparing the pawn capture with} 
14... a5 {is also possible.} 15. Rad1 a4 16. Bc4 Bxd4 17. e5 Ra7 18. Bh6 c5 19.
e6 f5 {with excellent compensation for the exchange.}) 15. Rad1 c5 16. Bd5 Nd7
17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Bxe7 Re8 19. Bxc5 $1 {Without this important resource White
would be just worse.} Ne5 20. Qf6 Bxc5 21. Rd5 Bf8 22. Rxe5 Rc8 23. Rd5 Qb7 24.
Rd8 Rxd8 25. Qxd8 c2 26. Rc1 Qb1 27. Qd2 Ba3 28. Qd8+ {with a draw by
perpetual.}) (10. cxb4 {is fine from structural point of view as White's
queenside structure looks more compact, but it offers Black free piece play.}
Qxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxd4 12. Rb1 Ba6 13. Bb2 Bxb2 14. Rxb2 Nd7 15. Nf3 (15. f4 {
as tried in Atalik-Tukmakov, Tilburg 1993 is simplest met with} e5 {causing
White some structural problems, too.}) 15... e6 $5 {Black usually castles
short, but the king is better placed close to the center.} 16. Kd2 Ke7 17. Rc2
(17. Rc1 Rhc8 18. a4 Rab8 $11) 17... Rhc8 18. Rhc1 Bb7 19. Ke3 (19. Nd4 c5 20.
bxc5 Bxe4 $11) 19... a5 $11) 10... O-O 11. Ne2 bxc3 12. Qxc3 ({Even though not
too popular the insertion of} 12. h4 h5 {makes some sense:} 13. Qxc3 Bb7 ({
One important difference is that} 13... Ba6 14. Be3 Nd7 15. Qxc6 Nb6 {allows}
16. Qxg6 $18) 14. Bg5 {Sooner or later the vulnerability of the h4-pawn will
force White placing his bishop on g5, thus leaving d4 somewhat weak.} (14. O-O
c5 15. Qxc5 Bxe4 16. Bg5 Nd7 $11 {Sokolov-Timman, Malmo 1997. The point is that
} 17. Qxe7 Qxe7 18. Bxe7 Rfe8 {leads to mass simplifications:} 19. Bg5 Bd3 20.
Ba4 Nf8 21. Bxe8 Rxe8 22. Ng3 Bxf1 23. Kxf1 Bxd4 $11) 14... Na6 15. Rd1 c5 16.
O-O {In Kallai-Adorjan, Hungary 1993 Blac took on d4 offering White some
initiative in a symmetrical position. He could have tried:} Rc8 17. Qe3 c4 18.
Bc2 Nb4 $132) ({Another fine game of Adorjan went} 12. O-O Ba6 13. Rd1 c5 14.
dxc5 Qa5 15. e5 Nc6 16. Qxc6 Bxe2 17. Re1 c2 18. Rxe2 Qc3 $17 {
Groszpeter-Adorjan, Hungary 1992.}) 12... Ba6 (12... Bb7 $5) 13. Be3 (13. Bc4
c5 $15 {Stimpel-Henrich, Germany 1999.}) 13... Nd7 14. Qxc6 (14. Bc4 Bxc4 15.
Qxc4 c5 {offers Black easy play, Chaplin-Delphine, Massy 1993.}) 14... Nb6 {
Black has active minor pieces and is better developed. White will need some
time to get his king into safety, thus yielding Black an excellent compensation
for the pawn.} 15. e5 (15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Qd2 e5 17. d5 Nc4 18. Bxc4 Rxc4 19. f3
Qc8 20. Rc1 Rxc1+ 21. Qxc1 f5 22. Qxc8 Rxc8 23. Kd2 Rb8 24. Nc1 Rb2+ 25. Kc3
Rxg2 26. Bxa7 Bh6 $11) (15. Qc3 Qd7 (15... Rc8 16. Qa5 $1 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Bxd4
18. Rad1 e5 19. h4 $14) 16. Qd2 Nc4 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Rd1 (18. O-O Bxe2 19.
Qxe2 Bxd4 20. Rad1 e5 $11) 18... Qa4 $36) 15... Rc8 16. Qf3 Na4 17. Bd2 (17.
Bxa4 Qa5+ 18. Kf1 Qxa4 $17 {leaves White poorly coordinated.}) 17... Bxe2 18.
Qxe2 Qxd4 19. O-O Nc5 (19... e6 $11) 20. Bg5 (20. e6 Nxb3 21. exf7+ Kxf7 22.
axb3 Rc2 $11) 20... Qxe5 21. Qxe5 Bxe5 22. Rae1 Bf6 23. Bxf6 exf6 24. Re7 Nxb3
25. axb3 Rc3 26. Rxa7 $15 {½-½ Maksimenko-Staniszewski, Krynica 1998.} *

