1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Be2 {This move does not take measures against Black's increasing pressure
against d4. This implies hat very soon he will either have to make a
positional concession or sacrifice material. The difference on
the 7.Rb1 line is that the rook is within the g7-bishop's range, so in the
main line White will sacrifice a whole exchange and not only a pawn.} Nc6 9. d5
{The principled reaction.} (9. Be3 Bg4 {leaves White short of positionally
constructive continuations.} 10. e5 (10. d5 $2 {loses material without any
shadow of compensation:} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Bxc3+ 12. Kf1 Bxa1 13. Qxa1 Nd4 $17) (
10. Ng1 {is not very scary of course, but Black can even take over the
initiative:} Qa5 $3 $15 11. Bxg4 $2 cxd4 {Due to the permanent threats ...
Qxc3+ and ...dxc3 White needs choosing the squares for his bishop with care.}
12. Bf4 g5 13. Bg3 h5 $19 {Black wins one of the bishops for if} 14. Bxh5 dxc3)
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Bxe2 14. Kxe2 O-O {with
perfect play for Black.}) 9... Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4
13. Qxd4 O-O {White obviously has compensation for the exchange due to his
strong bishops and space advantage. But Black can stabilize the position and
maintain approximate equality.} 14. O-O (14. Bh6 {allows} Qa5+ 15. Kf1 f6 16.
Bxf8 (16. Bc4 $6 Rf7 17. Ke2 Bd7 $17 18. d6 e6 $19 {Berreth-Liepold,
Uttenreuth 1996.}) 16... Kxf8 {White has retrieved the material, but Black's
stability on dark squares makes the position balanced.} 17. g4 Bd7 18. e5 fxe5
19. Qxe5 Kg8 20. Kg2 Qc5 21. Bf3 Qd6 22. Qe3 b6 $11 {Lerner-Malaniuk, Yalta
1982.}) 14... Re8 $5 {Taking the rook out of the bishop's range and preparing.
..e7-e5.} 15. Bc3 (15. e5 $2 Be6 $1 16. d6 {After this forced move White loses
his domination.} (16. Bc4 Bxd5 $1 {wins a pawn due to the hanging bishops along
the d-file.}) 16... Qb6 17. Qf4 Rad8 18. Be3 Qb2 $17 {Sulypa-De la Villa
Garcia, Ubeda 1999.}) (15. Bc4 e5 16. Qd3 Bd7 17. f4 Rc8 {Just one of the
playable moves.} 18. fxe5 ({There is no time for prophylactic measures:} 18.
Bb3 Qb6+ 19. Be3 Bb5 20. Qd2 Qd6 $17) 18... Rxc4 19. Qxc4 Qb6+ 20. Rf2 (20. Kh1
Bb5) 20... Qb1+ 21. Qf1 Qxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Rxe5 $11 {Mohr-Smejkal, Germany 1988.})
(15. Bh6 $146 e5) 15... e5 16. Qd2 {The most flexible retreat.} (16. dxe6 $2
Qxd4 17. exf7+ Kxf7 18. Bxd4 Rxe4 19. Bc4+ Be6 $19) (16. Qb4 {fails to keep d6
under control for too long.} a5 17. Qa3 (17. Qb5 b6 {threatening either ...Ba6
or ...Bd7 with further queenside expansion.}) (17. Qb2 Qd6 {stabilizies the
position.}) 17... Bd7 {followed by ...b7-b5-b4.}) 16... Bd7 17. f4 f6 {White's
position is active but Black can keep his stability on dark squares. In
emergency cases, sacrificing the rook for the dark-squared bishop is likely to
yield approximate equality.} 18. fxe5 $6 {There was no rush with opening the
f-file.} (18. h3 $5 Rc8 19. fxe5 fxe5 20. d6 Qb6+ 21. Kh2 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Qxd6
23. Qb3+ Be6 24. Qxb7 Qe7 $11) (18. Ba5 $5 {is the best way of maintainin ghte
tension. Even though this loses two temi, it is important to deprive the queen
of the b6-square.} b6 19. Bc3 Qc7 20. fxe5 fxe5 21. Bb4 a5 22. Ba3 b5 23. Rc1
Qb7 24. Bc5 b4 {The position remains unclear but Black already has an active
plan based on creating a queenside passed pawn.}) 18... fxe5 19. Bc4 Qb6+ 20.
Kh1 {Boor-Kudrin, Dayton 2016.} Rac8 $1 21. Bb3 Rf8 $15 {Suddenly White
experiences problems along the f-file and on the bac rank.} *

