1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bg5 {
A very recent discovery. Except for one game, this was not played
before 2004. The move surely looks illogical as it does not contribute to the
defense of the d4-pawn, making the center looking vulnerable. White's idea
will be explained slightly later, but such a move cannot pose real
problems whatsoever.} c5 8. Rc1 O-O ({White's idea is that if Black reacts in
the same way as in the main lines with Be3, the e7-pawn will start hanging at
some point for instance:} 8... Qa5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. Nf3 {and the potential
threat Bxe7 restricts Black's possibilities.}) 9. Nf3 (9. d5 Qd6 {is likely to
transpose to the main line. The only way of avoiding this is delaying the
knight's development, but this is not dangerous for Black.} 10. Qd2 {The best
try.} (10. Be2 f5 $11) (10. Bd3 Nd7 11. Ne2 f5 12. exf5 Ne5 $15 {
Housieaux-Vachier Lagrave, Le Port-Marly 2011 The point is that White cannot
embark pawn grabbing:} 13. fxg6 $2 Qxd5 $19) ({If} 10. Nf3 {Black should
transpose to the main line with 10...Bg4 since} f5 $2 11. Bc4 {threatening Bxe7
} Kh8 12. e5 $1 {is very unpleasant.}) 10... f5 11. Bc4 Re8 (11... Rf7 $2 {
Timoshenko-Volokitin, Mamaia 2012} 12. Bf4 $1 Be5 13. Bxe5 Qxe5 14. Nf3 Qxe4+
15. Be2 $16) 12. Bf4 (12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Nf3 Nd7 $11) (12. Ne2 Nd7 13. exf5 Ne5
14. Bb5 Bxf5 15. Bxe8 Nd3+ 16. Kf1 Nxc1 $15) 12... e5 $11) 9... Bg4 10. d5 Qd6
$5 {Black aims to keep the position blocked. It should be mentioned that in
the Gruenfeld Defence the d6-square is frequently occupied by the queen.} 11.
Be2 ({If} 11. Qd2 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nd7 {White's center is not too mobile, making
it vulnerable to ...f7-f5. The point is that} 13. f4 {runs into} f6 14. Bh4 Bh6
15. Bg3 f5 $15 16. e5 $2 Nxe5 $1 {The question arises: what is the bishop
doing on g5 after all?}) 11... Nd7 12. h3 {By provoking the exchange on f3,
White aims to discourage ...f5 once and forever.} (12. c4 $5 {would have
prevented the black queenside expansion. But Black could use the tempo for
opening the other wing with} f5 $5) (12. O-O f5 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 b5 $1
({After the previous exchange,} 13... f5 {would have left the e6-square weak.})
14. c4 b4 15. O-O a5 $132 {The queenside majority is not less dangerous than
the massive white center.} 16. Bg4 Bd4 17. Re1 e5 {They say that the queen is
the worst possible blocking piece. Well, in the Gruenfeld there seems to be an
exception to this rule...} 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Be3 Bxe3 20. Rxe3 a4 $11 {The
permanent threat of creating a passed pawn with ...b3 does not offer White
free hands for a kingside attack. Nyback-Svidler, Khanty-Mansiysk 2009} *

