1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 {
This is the classical main line in the exchange system. White prepares
to develop the knight to e2, to avoid the pin with ...Bg4, thus
ensuring the integrity of his center. But at the same time, the Knight may
have to stay passive for a long while, moreover failing to control the
relatively weak c4-square. All these make the position very sharp
strategically and frequently tactically, too. One significant problem when
building up a repertoire (for either color) is that the system has been
heavily analyzed and one cannot deal without analyzing a whole bunch of forced
lines too easily. But there still is such an insufficiently deeply examined
area, if Black refrains from the usual ...c7-c5 in favour of ...Nc6. This
is how I mainly met 7.Bc4 in practice and this is the system I will examine now.
By refraining from an early ...c7-c5, Black keeps some mystery about his real
intentions. In principle, his main way of breaking the center is ...e7-e5, but e
will see that this has to be carried out with some care.} O-O 8. Ne2 ({If White
expects ...Nc6, he could delay the own knight's development with} 8. Be3 {
which is a useful move in all the lines with ...c7-c5, too. But after}
Nc6 9. Nf3 {the pinning ...Bg4 is at least as useful for the blockading plan
as in the lines with ...c7-c5.} e5 {White has three main ways of reacting.} 10.
Rc1 (10. d5 {this is premature. Blocking the center makes sense after Black
has developed his bishop to b7 already, forcing him to waste time for
regrouping.} Na5 11. Be2 b6 {This is the start of a global regrouping, typical
for this system. The following game is a good model showing that Black's
position has more potential despite his relative lack of space.} 12. c4 Nb7 13.
Nd2 Bd7 14. Rc1 c5 15. O-O Nd6 16. a4 a5 17. Rb1 Rb8 18. Bd3 f5 19. exf5 gxf5
20. f3 Qe7 21. Re1 Kh8 22. Bf2 Bf6 23. Kh1 Qg7 24. Qc2 Rg8 25. Bf1 Bg5 {
With obvious initiative Shirov-Stohl, Brno 1991.}) (10. h3 {prevents ...Bg4
aiming at maintaining the tension, but Black can use this waste of time by
attacking e4:} exd4 11. cxd4 Qe7 12. O-O $5 ({Relatively best as White cannot
defend e4 under favorable circumstances:} 12. Bd3 $2 Nxd4 $1 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14.
Nxd4 Qb4+ $17) (12. Qc2 Nb4 13. Qb1 c5 $11) 12... Qxe4 13. Re1 {
Christiansen-Kindermann, Munich 1991} Na5 $1 {The best way of solving the
problem with the exposed queen is ready to sacrifice it! If the bishop
retreats, the queen will comfortably go to d5, so the next line is forced:} 14.
Bd2 Qxe1+ 15. Bxe1 Nxc4 16. Rc1 b5 $11 {Material is about equal, and Black has
two active bishops and a stable knight.}) 10... Bg4 11. d5 Na5 12. Be2 (12. Bd3
{allows Black in dissolving the center:} c6 13. c4 b5 14. dxc6 Bxf3 15. gxf3 b4
16. c5 Nxc6 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nc4 14. Bc5 Re8 {I have examined the
following sequence in my previous strategical article. I insert part of the
comments here.} {White has several ways of attacking the active knight, but
they all have drawbacks.} 15. Qd3 (15. Be2 Nd6 {safely blocks the d-pawn
gaining time by attacking the e4-pawn.}) (15. Qb3 {also allows Black gaining
time:} Na5 16. Qa4 b6 17. O-O c6 $5 18. Bb4 cxd5 19. Bxa5 bxa5 20. exd5 Rb8 21.
Rfd1 Bf8 {With perfect stability on dark squares and a potentially dangerous
central majority. White preferred a centralizing move}) 15... b5 $1 ({Much
stronger than the natural} 15... Nd6 16. c4 b6 17. Be3 {with initiative.}) 16.
Qb1 Qd7 17. Rd1 Bf8 $1 {This exchange leaves White with a potentially bad
bishop, while the knight remains the dominating minor piece.} 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19.
O-O c5 {With obvious advantage for Black.}) 8... Nc6 9. O-O ({Trying to inhibit
...e7-e5 with} 9. Ba3 {is a bit clumsy. This move openly invites Black
switching to the plan based on ...Na5, ...b7-b6, ...Bb7 and ...c7-c5, since
on some positions examined in the first strategical chapter the
promising plan with Be3-h6 is not available any more.} Na5 10. Bd3 b6 11. O-O
c5 $1 {A typical pawn sacrifice.} 12. dxc5 ({Keeping the tension offers little
as the bishop stands miserably on a3.} 12. Rc1 Bb7 13. d5 f5 14. f3 fxe4 15.
fxe4 Rxf1+ 16. Qxf1 e6 17. c4 Qd6 $15) 12... Qc7 13. cxb6 axb6 {We are
familiar with this kind of queenside structures from the strategic articles.
White's pawns are too weak to allow hoping him for an advantage and the night
stands badly.} 14. Qc2 Nc6 15. Bb2 Ne5 16. Nd4 (16. Bb5 Ng4 17. g3 {causes
White additional weaknesses.} Ne5 18. Nd4 Nc4 $11) 16... Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Ba6 18.
Nb5 Qf4 19. a4 Rfd8 (19... Rad8 {is slightly more logical. It not only keeps
the other rook on f8 to prepare ...f7-f5 but also avoids the later fork with
Nc7.} 20. Qf3 Qxf3 21. gxf3 Rd3 22. Kg2 f5 $15) 20. Qf3 (20. Qc4 $2 {
Hajek-Blees, Vienna 1990} Be5 $1 21. g3 Qf3 $17 {The threats ...Bc8-h3 or
simply ...Bb7 cause White lots of problems. For instance} 22. Rae1 Rd3 {
preventing Re3.}) 20... Qxf3 21. gxf3 Bb7 22. Bc1 f5 $11) ({In other lines
without ...c7-c5, for instance, Timman's specialty 8...b6, White usually
launches a kingside attack. But here} 9. h4 {is ineffective as the the knight
on c6 Black can react in the center at once. The following notes are taken
from my last strategic article.} e5 $1 {Of course, the best reaction against
an attack on the wing is a counter-blow in the center.} 10. Be3 Qe7 {[%csl Rc4,
Re4][%cal Ge5d4]} 11. d5 Na5 12. Bd3 f5 {With his king in the center yet and
the attack not going, White faces some problems despite his advantage
in space.} 13. Qa4 b6 14. h5 f4 15. Bc1 Bd7 16. Bb5 Bxb5 17. Qxb5 {White has
managed to provoke the favourable exchange of the light-squared
bishops, but with his poor development, this is a questionable achievement.
Among other things, the c4-square is vulnerable and the e2-knight rather
passive.} c6 $1 18. Qd3 ({White tries keeping his center together as after} 18.
dxc6 {retrieving the c6-pawn would be just a matter of time for Black when
the weakness of the c-pawn and the c4-square would offer him a consistent
advantage.}) 18... g5 $1 {Ultimately removing the possibility of an attack
along the h-file.} 19. a4 g4 {[%cal Gf4f3]} 20. Ba3 c5 {White has managed
to block the center, but this does not affect Black, whose knight controls the
c4-square.} 21. f3 Bf6 22. c4 {[%cal Ge2c3] Planning Nc3 with reasonable
coordination.} Rad8 $1 {[%cal Ga5c6,Gc6d4] A strong move preventing White's
regrouping by threatening to transfer the knight to d4 with ...Nc6. White's
knight is awfully passive now.} 23. Qc2 {Now, White cannot play Nc3 anymore.}
Kh8 24. O-O-O Rg8 $15 {White has evacuated the king from the center, but the
queenside is not an entirely safe residence either.} 25. Ng1 {Planning to meet
gxf3 with Nxf3, getting some stability. In Kapnisis-Marin, Plovdiv 2008
Black's best was} Qb7 $17 {followed by ...a7-a6 and ...b6-b5 with a
devastating attack.}) 9... b6 $1 ({Black should complete his development
before undertaking anything concrete. If} 9... e5 $2 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Bxf7+ Kxf7
12. Qb3+ Be6 (12... Kf6 13. Rad1 {yields White a decisive attack since the
king and queen do not have safe squares available.}) 13. d5 Na5 14. Qa4 c6 15.
dxe6+ $16) 10. Bg5 {Pinning the e-pawn is not too effective since Black
usually does not hurry with breaking in the center anyway.} ({This is the only
important alternative to} 10. Be3 {which is examined in the next line.}) ({
Preventing ...e7-e5 radically with} 10. e5 {offers Black easy play due to the
weakness on d5.} Na5 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. Be3 c5 13. Qd2 Rc8 14. Rac1 Qd7 {and
White is slow in launching his standard attack with h4-h5 and Bh6.}) 10... Bb7
11. Qd2 Qd6 {As we will see in the next line, a typical queen's development.}
12. Rad1 (12. e5 $2 {loses a pawn:} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qc6 14. Bxf7+ Rxf7 15. f3
Bxe5) 12... Na5 ({It is useful inserting this move before breaking the center
as} 12... e5 13. Bd5 {causes Black some problems.}) 13. Bd3 e5 (13... c5 14. d5
e6 15. c4 {allows Wite keeping his space advantage as in two games played by
Gulko ith Black.}) 14. Bh6 {Shliperman-Kudrin, Salt Lake City 1999} Rfe8 15. f3
Rad8 $11 {Black is perfectly mobilized and has little to fear about.} *

