1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 O-O 8.
Ne2 Nc6 9. O-O b6 10. Be3 {This is the main tabiya and logically so. White
achieves the optimal regrouping for the 7.Bc4 system safely defending d4 and
keeping the flexibility of plan choice, mainly Qd2 and Bh6 but also f2-f4. This is
the case in most lines with ...c7-c5, too.} Bb7 11. Qd2 (11. f4 {deprives
White from the plan with Bh6 inviting Black switching to ...c7-c5:} Na5 12. Bd3
e6 {Planning ...f7-f5 with perfect stability.} 13. f5 exf5 14. exf5 Re8 15. Qd2
Qe7 16. Bf4 c5 {with pleasant and probably preferable play for Black, as
White's minor pieces are suddenly not so harmoniously placed, Kertesz-Stanciu,
Bucharest 1974.}) 11... Qd6 {In the absence of direct pawn contacts, White has
a wide choice at his disposal.} 12. Bh6 {The most straightforward move. True,
it looks more consistent to develop the queen's rook first but since Black has
not defined his intentions yet it is not easy to choose the right file.} (12.
Rad1 {is the most natural but it leaves the c-file (and in particular the
c4-square) insufficiently well defended, allowing Black switching to ...c7-c5:}
Na5 (12... e5 13. f4 {offers his attacking chances.}) 13. Bd3 c5 14. Bf4 (14.
d5 f5 $11) 14... Qd7 15. Bh6 cxd4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. cxd4 Rac8 {on
the generally favorable lines for White, he now has to waste a tempo due to
the threat ...Nc4. This maks quite some difference as Black manages to regroup
properly.} 18. Rc1 e6 19. h4 Nc6 20. Qb2 Kg8 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 22. Bb1 Qe7 23. h5
Qg5 24. hxg6 hxg6 25. Rc3 Qf6 26. Rd2 Na5 {White has no attacking chances at
all, and Black's position is already more pleasant as White's minor pieces are
badly placed, Shemeakin-Popov, Kaliningrad 2015.}) ({Anticipating ...c7-c5 with
} 12. Rac1 {is clumsy as Black has the plan with ...e7-e5, too.} Rad8 $146 13.
Rfd1 {It is hard imagining a more constructive move, but now White is
distracted from his kingside attacking plan.} e5 14. f4 (14. Bd5 Na5 $11) 14...
Qe7 $1 15. Bd5 (15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Bb3 Ng4 17. Bg5 Qxe4 18. Ng3 Qc6 $15 19. Bxd8
$2 Rxd8 $19 {The threat ...Bh6 is killing.}) 15... exd4 16. cxd4 Rxd5 17. exd5
Nb4 {with fantastic compensation for the exchange.}) (12. f4 {is best met with
the familiar} Na5 13. Bd3 c5 14. f5 cxd4 15. cxd4 Rac8 {Roorda-Van Haastert,
Leiden 2012.}) ({And of course} 12. e5 $2 {runs into} Nxe5 $19) 12... e5 {
As we know from the revuous strategic article, the bishops exchange is best
met with the blocking strategy.} 13. Rad1 (13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. f4 {
Celestino-Ripari, Mar del Plata 2006} Rae8 $1 {Putting pressure on e4 and
taking advantage of the pin along the d-file.} 15. f5 f6 16. Bd5 Ba6 $1 {
White faces the danger of losing stability.}) 13... Rad8 14. Rfe1 ({Black is
well prepared against the plan with f2-f4:} 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 (15. Bd5 Ba6)
15... f5 16. Qe3 (16. exf5 exd4 17. cxd4 Rxf5) (16. fxe5 $2 Nxe5 $1 $17) 16...
exd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Rxd4 Qc5 (18... Qe7 19. e5 c5 20. Rdd1 $14) 19. e5 Rxd4
20. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 21. cxd4 Rd8 22. Rd1 {This ending is optically better for White
but in fact it is just drawish.} Bd5 23. Bxd5 Rxd5 24. Rc1 Rxd4 25. Rxc7+ Kg8
26. Rxa7 (26. g3 Ra4 27. Kf2 Rxa2+ 28. Ke3 Ra4 $11) (26. e6 Rxf4 $11) 26...
Rxf4 $11) 14... Na5 (14... Rfe8 $5) 15. Bd3 c5 16. Bxg7 (16. d5 f5 {offers
Black ample counterplay.}) 16... Kxg7 17. dxe5 Qxe5 {Black has eliminated the
danger of an attack and keeps the better structure.} 18. Qf4 Rfe8 19. f3 Bc6
20. Qxe5+ Rxe5 21. Kf2 Ba4 22. Bc2 Rxd1 23. Bxd1 Bb5 24. Bb3 Nc4 25. Rd1 Nb2 (
25... a5 $2 {Careless.} 26. a4 Ba6 27. Rd7 $18 {Ivkov-Timman, Hilversum 1973})
26. Rd8 Bd3 27. Ke3 c4 $15 *

