1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 {The Russian
system is one of the most ambitious ways of meeting the Gruenfeld. White builds
up a massive center without allowing the exchange of one knight and without
offering Black the standard plan based on ...c7-c5. The main drawback of this
system is wasting time with the queen who, to all probability, will soon
have to move again.} O-O 7. e4 {The only challenging move.} (7. Bf4 Be6 $1 {
This is the simplest way of solving Black's problems.} ({Curiously, in practice
} 7... c6 {and}) (7... Na6 {are by far more popular.}) 8. Qxc7 {Otherwise the
previous move would make little sense as Black could continue with ...Nc6
anyway.} Nc6 9. Qxd8 ({If} 9. Qxb7 {as in Berkes-Vachier Lagrave, Paks 2008
the simplest is} Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. e3 Qc5 {Black's advance in development
and the pressure against the enemy queenside offer him at least adequate
compensation for the pawn.}) ({Delaying the queen exchange does not make much
of a difference as play is likely to transpose:} 9. e3 Nb4 10. Kd2 Nbd5 {
White does better taking on d8 for if} 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {the queen's presence
causes the White king additional problems.}) 9... Rfxd8 10. e3 Nb4 11. Kd2 (11.
Rc1 Nxa2) 11... Nbd5 12. Nxd5 (12. Bg3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Ne4+ {loses the c3-pawn
soon with overwhelming initiative due to the uncastled king.}) 12... Ne4+ $1
13. Ke1 Bxd5 {Black has a huge lead in development and White has lost the right
to castle. Black's immediate threat is ...Rac8-c2.} 14. Bd3 ({Trying to defend
against the intrusion along the c-file for if} 14. Be2 Rac8) 14... Nc5 $5 15.
Be2 (15. dxc5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Rxd3 17. Ke2 Rd5 $11) 15... Ne4 16. Bd3 Nc5 17. Bc2
Ne6 18. Bg3 Rac8 19. Bd1 {Avoiding the repetition and the drawish simplifying
put White in some danger. In Wojtaszek-Tomczak, Poland 2013 Black could have
fought for more than adequate compensation for the pawn with} Nc5 20. dxc5 (20.
Be2 Na4 21. b3 Nc3 22. Bd3 $6 Nxa2 $1) 20... Bxb2 21. Be5 (21. Rb1 Bc3+ 22. Kf1
Bxa2 23. Rc1 Bb2 $19) 21... Bxa1 22. Bxa1 Rxc5 $15 {Material is equal, but the
a2-pawn is as good as lost ad White still does not have a clear way of
activating his rook.}) (7. g3 {developing the bishop to g2 does not fit well
together with the queen on c4, not in the Gruenfeld defense at least (The
Catalan is a different story as Black does not have pressure on d4).} Be6 8.
Qa4 (8. Qd3 c5 9. dxc5 Na6 $15) (8. Qb5 Nc6 $11) 8... Nc6 9. Bg2 Nd7 {As we
will soon find out this is a typical maneuver with the queen exposed. The
knight is heading for b6 clearing the bishop's path with a gain of time.} 10. O-O
(10. e3 {consolidates the d4 pawn but weakens the f1-a6 diagonal.} Nb6 11. Qc2
Bc4 12. Bf1 {Zuluaga Mancilla-Martinez Romero, Silvania 2011} e5 $15) 10... Nb6
11. Qc2 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Bxb7 (13. Rd1 {M. Karlsson-F. Olafsson,
Reykjavik 2012} Qb4 14. Bxb7 Rad8 $132) 13... Rab8 14. Bg2 {Black's activity
and the pressure against the underdeveloped queenside compensates for the pawn
weaknesses. In Flohr-Botvinnik, Moscow 1952 the simplest way to equality was}
Nc4 15. Rb1 (15. Rd1 {makes} Na3 {even stronger.}) 15... Na3 16. bxa3 Qxc3 $11)
7... Bg4 {This is one of the oldest systems of defense, designed by Vassily
Smyslov. Black plans setting up piece pressure against the enemy center with
the following coherent plan: ...Nfd7-b6, ...Nc6 and ...e7-e5 or if d4-d4 then .
..Ne5 or ...Na5 followed by either ...e7-e6 or ...c7-c6.} ({Nowadays the
forcing} 7... Na6 {and}) (7... a6 {are more popular but I find the Smyslov
setup quite logical with the important positive side that it does not require
memorizing long forced lines. All it takes is understanding he position.}) {
In this section, we will examine White's sidelines on the move 8.} 8. Ne5 {A
radical attempt to question the viability of Black's plans, as the bishop did
not pin the knight one move earlier.} (8. Ng5 {has a similar idea but puts
less pressure on Black.} Nc6 9. d5 (9. Be3 e5 10. d5 Nd4 $15 11. Bxd4 $2 exd4
12. Qxd4 $2 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Qxg5 $19) {Najdorf-Ragozin, Saltsjobaden 1948} 9...
Ne5 $146 10. Qd4 (10. Qb3 h6 11. h3 Bc8 12. f4 hxg5 13. fxe5 Nh5 14. Bxg5 Bxe5
{with at least equal play.}) 10... Nh5 11. Qe3 h6 12. h3 Bd7 13. Nf3 Nxf3+ 14.
Qxf3 c6 {with adequate counterplay. White still needs completing his
development while his centre is not that impressive anyore.}) (8. e5 {does not
disturb Black as he was going to play} Nfd7 {anyway.}) (8. Be2 Nfd7 9. Be3 {
transposes to the next line.}) ({And} 8. Be3 Nfd7 {is just the next line.})
8... Be6 9. Qd3 {The most challenging move. The queen is relatively stable and
defends the d4-pawn.} (9. d5 {gains even more time, but exposes White even
more.} Bc8 10. Be2 e6 11. O-O exd5 12. exd5 Ne8 13. Bf4 Nd6 14. Qd3 Nd7 $11 {
Kotov-Lilienthal, Parnu 1947.}) (9. Qa4 Nfd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 {gains time for
Black, leaving the d4-pawn vulnerable.}) (9. Qb4 {exposes the queen to} Nfd7
10. Nxd7 Nc6 $1 11. Qxb7 Bxd7 12. d5 Rb8 13. Qa6 Nb4 14. Qe2 c6 $15 {Hoang,
T-Flumbort, Budapest 2002.}) 9... Na6 $1 $146 {The only way of questioning the
queen's stability.} 10. Qd2 {For hidden reasons this is relatively best even
though it looks awkward.} (10. Be2 $2 {loses a pawn to} Nb4 11. Qd1 Qxd4 $1) (
10. Be3 {allows} c5 11. dxc5 (11. d5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bf5 13. Nxf7 Rxf7 {with
initiative.}) 11... Qc7 $15 {retrieving the pawn with inititive.}) (10. a3 {
allows} Bb3 $1 {followed by ...c7-c5.}) (10. Qd1 {is inferor due to} Nb4 {
Threatening ...Qxd4.} 11. d5 Nxe4 $1 12. Nxe4 Qxd5 $19 {White's knights and
the a1-rook are hanging. ith the queen on d2 this does not work so well due to
Qxb4.}) 10... Ng4 11. Nf3 c5 12. d5 Bd7 13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. h3 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5
16. O-O Qb6 17. Qc2 Rab8 18. Rb1 f5 $11 {with adequate counterplay.} *

