1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Bg4 8.
Be3 {The main move, consolidating the d4-pawn in anticipation of Black's plan.}
Nfd7 9. Rd1 {The most reliable move, continuing to consolidate the central pawn
without exposing the king. True, His Majesty needs staying in the center for a
while now.} (9. O-O-O {is more constructive strictly from the point of view of
development, but the king is exposed on the queenside.} Nb6 {White has tried
several moves here.} 10. Qc5 (10. Qb3 e6 {This is similar to the plan from the
next line. Blck prepares ...Nc6 reducing the impact of d4-d5.} 11. Ne2 {
Eljanov-Mamedyarov, Plovdiv 2010} Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qh4 {(Stohl)} 13. Kb1 Nc6 14.
Rg1 Rfd8 15. Rg3 (15. Bg5 Qxh2 16. Rg2 Qd6 17. Bxd8 Rxd8 {offers Black great
compensation on dark squares.}) 15... Qe7 {Space started becoming narrow for
the queen, so it is best to retreat and parry the threat Bg5.} 16. Bg5 Bf6 $11)
(10. Qd3 Nc6 11. Be2 Qc8 ({Preparing ...e7-e5 for if} 11... e5 12. d5 Bxf3 13.
dxc6 Qxd3 14. Rxd3 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 bxc6 16. Rc3 $14) 12. Qc2 {Pachman-Keres,
Moscow 1947} Rd8 13. d5 Nb4 14. Qb3 c5 {Black has excellent counterplay. White
does better not trying to fight gainst the apparently unstable b4-knight:} 15.
a3 $6 a5 $1 16. axb4 axb4 17. Nb5 (17. Nb1 Ra1 {is awfully passive. Black will
continue with ...Qa8 and ...Bd7-a4.}) 17... Ra4 18. Kd2 c4 19. Qc2 b3 20. Qc1
Nxd5 21. exd5 Rxd5+ 22. Nfd4 e5 $17) 10... e5 $1 {The correct move order,
cutting the queen's access to g5.} (10... N8d7 11. Qg5 {causes Black some
problems as ...e7-e5 allows the queen exchange with lower prospects for
counterplay.}) 11. dxe5 N8d7 12. Qa5 Qe8 13. Be2 {Thorhallsson-E. Hansen,
Reykjavik 2015} Nxe5 $11 14. Bc5 {This may be what Black feared, but it only
causes problems to White.} Nec4 15. Bxc4 (15. Qb4 $2 Nxb2 $1 16. Bxf8 Qxf8 17.
Qxf8+ Rxf8 18. Kxb2 Na4+ 19. Kc2 Nxc3 $17) 15... Nxc4 16. Qb4 Nd6 17. Bxd6 cxd6
18. Rxd6 Rc8 $15 {followed by ...b7-b5 and ...Rc4 with strong initiative.}) (9.
Nd2 {is quite passive and it does not create Black problems with his bishop.}
Nb6 10. Qd3 Nc6 11. d5 (11. Nb3 {Fredouille-Chaude de Silans, Besancon 1949} f5
12. h3 fxe4 {Either capture on e4 would cause White problems after ...Bf5} 13.
Qd2 Be6 14. Nc5 Bf7 15. Nxb7 Qb8 16. Nc5 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Rd8 $15) 11... Ne5 12.
Qc2 Bd7 {Preparing the next move and creating the possibility of ...Ng4,
especially after f2-f4.} 13. h3 e6 $11 14. f4 $2 Qh4+ 15. Kd1 Ng4 $19) (9. Ng5
{is similar.} Nb6 10. Qd3 Nc6 11. h3 Bc8 12. Nf3 f5 13. e5 f4 14. Bc1 Bf5 15.
Qd1 {Tomovic-Gligoric, Zagreb 1949} Nb4 $1 16. Qb3+ N6d5 17. Nxd5 Nc2+ $1 18.
Kd1 Nxa1 {The queen is hanging so discovered checks are not dangerous.} 19. Qc4
Be6 20. Nf6+ Rxf6 $19) ({The developing} 9. Be2 {leaves the d4-pawn vulnerable.}
Nb6 10. Qc5 (10. Qd3 Nc6 11. Rd1 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 e5 13. d5 Nd4 {Black has no
problems at all, but it is interesting to follow how he carries out the most
logical plan.} 14. Be2 c6 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. O-O Qe7 17. Rd2 Rfd8 18. Qa6 Bf6
19. Rfd1 Bg5 $11 {Fressinet-Ruck, Ohrid 2009}) 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 (11. Bxf3 {
allows} Na6 {winning the d4-pawn.}) 11... e5 12. d5 N8d7 13. Qa5 {
Ivanchuk-Ftacnik, Istanbul 2000} Qh4 14. O-O-O Bh6 $11) ({The absolute main
move} 9. Qb3 {is examined in the next line.}) 9... Nb6 10. Qc5 (10. Qb3 {
transposes to the next line.}) 10... e5 ({Once again, ith the queen on c5 it
is best to cut its access to g5.} 10... N8d7 11. Qg5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 e5 13. Qxd8
Rfxd8 14. d5 $14 {Ward-Morris, Blackpool 1988.}) 11. dxe5 (11. d5 {leads to a
familiar scenario:} N8d7 12. Qb5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Qh4 {><b5} 14. Rc1 Bh6 $15)
11... N8d7 12. Qa3 (12. Qb5 c6 13. Qb4 Bxf3 $1 (13... Qc7 14. Qd6 Qc8 15. e6
Bxe6 16. Bd4 {offered White some light pressure in Cs. Horvath-Stohl, Stary
Smokovec 1991.}) 14. gxf3 Qh4 $15 {White cannot keep his extra pawn and will
have to struggle due to his worse structure and not entirely safe king. For
instance:} 15. f4 Bh6 16. Ne2 Nxe5 $1) 12... Qc8 13. e6 Bxe6 {Planning ...Re8,
...Bf8} 14. Bd4 Bh6 $1 {Threatening ...c5} 15. Nb1 Re8 16. Nbd2 a5 $36 17. Be2
Bf8 18. Qe3 Bxa2 19. Qf4 c5 20. Bc3 Na4 {White does not have enough
compensation for the pawn, Ubilava-Ehlvest, Kujbyshev 1986.} *

