1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Bg4 8.
Be3 Nfd7 9. Qb3 (9. Rd1 Nb6 10. Qb3 {is the same.}) 9... Nb6 10. Rd1 e6 ({
This move became popular much later than the old main line} 10... Nc6 11. d5 Ne5
12. Be2 Nxf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh5 {when Black faces some problems obtaining
counterplay. The main move's idea is reducing the impact of d4-d5 and thus
play ...Nc6 under more comfortable circumstances. Of course, White can use
this tempo for organizing the defense of the d4-pawn, but overall this is the
safest continuation for Black, offering him chances for counterplay, too.}) 11.
Be2 ({Trying to cause Black problems with ...Nc6 is not too effective:} 11. Bb5
Bxf3 ({The only thing to avoid is weakening the b6-square as} 11... a6 $6 12.
Be2 Nc6 13. d5 exd5 14. exd5 Ne5 {allows White} 15. d6 {with some initiative.
This resource is not available in the main line with the pawn on a7.}) 12. gxf3
Qh4 {This is a typical Grunfeld structure offering Black lots of active
possibilities due to White's weaknesses in dak squares. Of course White also
has his trumps, the bishops pair, and the space advantage, but these are things
a Gruenfeld player takes into account when playing his first three moves.
Here are some typical examples:} 13. a4 (13. Ne2 a6 14. Bd3 Nc6 15. Bb1 Rfd8
16. Rg1 Rd7 17. Rg2 Bh6 18. f4 Rad8 19. Rd3 Bg7 20. e5 {Forintos-Smejkal, Bar
1977} Bh6 $17) (13. e5 {Reshevsky-Shvidler, Beersheba 1982} a6 14. Bd3 Nc6 $132
) 13... a6 14. Be2 (14. a5 axb5 15. axb6 c6 $15 {Suba}) 14... Nc6 15. f4 Rad8
16. d5 exd5 17. exd5 (17. Bxb6 {Suba} Bxc3+ $1 18. bxc3 cxb6 19. exd5 Ne7 20.
c4 Qxf4 {With chronicl weaknesses on dark squares.}) 17... Na5 $1 18. Qa2 (18.
Qb4 Bxc3+ 19. Qxc3 Nxd5 $17 {The point is that the e3-bishop is hanging as the
f2-pawn is pinned.}) {Suba-Ftacnik, Dortmund 1981} 18... Qh3 $1 $19 {planning
Qg2, Bxc3+, Rxd5.}) (11. d5 {is completely inoffensive:} exd5 12. exd5 Bxf3 13.
gxf3 N8d7 14. f4 Re8 $15 {Paramasivam-Kiran, Mumbai 2008.}) 11... Nc6 12. Ng1 {
The least committal of the three ways of dealing with the threat on d4.} (12.
e5 {Generally speaking this offers Black some relief as he now has the
d5-square for his knights. But at the same time, this does not automatically
mean he has simple ways for counterplay. Besides, White hopes to use the
weakness of the f6-suare for an attack, but with his queen far from the
kingside this is just a long-term project.} a5 $1 {Gaining queenside space
before occupying d5 is the most effective plan.} 13. a3 {The most flexible way
of dealing with the advance of the a-pawn.} (13. O-O a4 14. Qc2 {
Lalith-Gallego Alcaraz, Badalona 2012} a3 $1 15. b3 Nb4 16. Qd2 N6d5 {The
queenside space advantage offers Black good chances in the long run.}) (13. h3
a4 14. Qc2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 {Grigorian-Torre, Baku 1980} Nb4 16. Qc1 N6d5 $11) (
13. a4 Nb4 {leaves the queen uncomfortable while also offering Black dream
stability.}) 13... a4 14. Qc2 ({A more recent game continued with the oddly
looking} 14. Qa2 Ne7 15. O-O Nf5 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 c6 18. Be4 Nxe3 19. fxe3
Qe7 20. Rf3 f6 21. exf6 Rxf6 22. Rxf6 Bxf6 $15 {Funny that White did not have
the time for activating his queen, Aleksandrov-Neverov, Minsk 2000.}) 14... Bf5
15. Qc1 Na5 {Threatening to trap the queen.} 16. Bg5 f6 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Bxf6
Qxf6 19. O-O Nb3 20. Qe3 Bc2 21. Rde1 {Both sides have played logically and
Black's freer play compensates for the weakness on e6 and White's space
advantage in the center.} Nd5 (21... Rae8 22. Bb5 $16) 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Bd3 (
23. Qc3 Qc6 $1 $17) (23. Ne5 Qf4) 23... Bxd3 $1 $146 (23... Rae8 $4 24. Qxe8 $1
{Uhlmann-Larsen, Las Palmas (m/8) 1971}) 24. Qxd3 Rae8 25. Re5 Rxe5 (25... c6
26. Rfe1) 26. dxe5 Qe6 $11 {The position remains interesting, but chances are
balanced. For instance:} 27. Re1 c6 28. Nd4 (28. Ng5 Qg4) 28... Nxd4 29. Qxd4 b5
$11) (12. d5 {is a premature display of activity.} exd5 13. exd5 (13. Nxd5 Nxd5
14. exd5 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 Bxe5 $15 {El Gindy-Ponomariov,
Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}) 13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Bxe5 16. O-O Re8 $11 {
Farago-Jansa, Austria 1996.}) 12... Bxe2 13. Ngxe2 {White has managed to keep
the integrity of his center, but the light-squared bishops exchange has
simplified Black's life.} Qe7 14. O-O (14. h4 Qb4 15. Qc2 {Piket-De Boer,
Hilversum 1990} Nc4 16. Bc1 Rad8) 14... Rfd8 {Black's counterplay develops
slowly but constantly. Apart from the pressure on d4, White has to count with.
..Qb4, raising the knight's queenside influence.} 15. e5 {This paradoxical
move seems to be the best. White reduces the pressure on d4 in anticipation of
...Bb4. At the same time, he prepares a slow attack with Ne4 and Bg5. All the
alternatives are easier to meet.} (15. a3 {Ftacnik: 'Bob' www.chesstoday.net:
'- main move' prevents ...Qb4 but weakens the queenside and offers Black an
important tempo.} Na5 ({Avoiding the trap} 15... Rd7 $6 16. Na4 $1 $14 Nxa4 $6
17. Qxb7 $1 $16) 16. Qb5 (16. Qc2 Nac4 {The knight is relatively stable here
due to the weakness of the a3-pawn.} 17. Bc1 c5 18. d5 exd5 19. exd5 Nd6 $11 {
With a promising blockade Bologan-Eljanov, Sochi 2005.}) 16... Nac4 17. Bg5 f6
18. Bc1 c6 19. Qb3 {Ivkov-Jansa, Skara 1980} Qf7 $5 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gf6f5]
Black will play either ...f6-f5 or ...e6-e5 according to the circumstances.}) (
15. f3 Rd7 $1 (15... Qb4 $11) 16. Kh1 (16. Na4 {does not work anymore due to
the weakness of the g1-a7 diagonal:} Rad8 $1 17. Nc5 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Rxd4 $1 19.
Rxd4 Bxd4 20. Nxb7 Nc4 $3 {with initiative.}) 16... Qb4 {Finally the thematic
move. Due to the pressure on d4, White cannot avoid the queen exchange.} 17.
Qxb4 (17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Bc1 Nxd4 $17) 17... Nxb4 18. Bf2 (18. b3 Nc2 19. Bf2 Rad8
20. Nb5 c5 $15) 18... Rad8 19. Bh4 Rc8 20. b3 Nc2 21. Bf2 Rcd8 22. Bh4 Ne3 $5 {
Ivanchuk has decided to simplify the position tactically, chances remain about
equal.} (22... f6 23. Bf2 f5 $11) 23. Bxd8 Rxd8 24. Rfe1 Nxd1 25. Rxd1 Bf8 26.
g3 c5 $11 {Radjabov-Ivanchuk, Dubai 2002.}) (15. d5 {Alexandria-Gaprindashvili,
Tskhaltubo 1988} exd5 16. exd5 Na5 17. Qc2 (17. Qb5 Nac4 18. Bc5 Nd6 $11) 17...
Nac4 $11) (15. Rfe1 $146 Qb4 $11) 15... Qb4 ({Many games continue with} 15...
h6 {which does not make much sense as White's attack has not started yet.}) 16.
Qc2 a5 $5 $146 {A known plan but a new move.} ({Here, too,} 16... h6 {is the
only tried move.}) 17. a3 (17. Ne4 a4 18. a3 Qc4 19. Rc1 (19. Qxc4 Nxc4 20. Rb1
b5) (19. Qd2 $2 Bxe5) 19... Qxc2 20. Rxc2 Nd5 $11) 17... Qc4 18. b3 Qa6 19. Ne4
(19. a4 Nb4 20. Qb1 N6d5 $11) 19... a4 20. b4 Qc4 $11 {Black's perfect control
on dark squares compensates for White's space advantage. Without queens, the
weakness of the f6-suare will lose relevance.} *

